kertome/w,  'I do not mock,' i.e. I do not say what I do not mean. Soph. Philoc. 1235:



*o*d. po/tera dh\ kertomw=n le/geis ta/de;

*n*e. ei) kerto/mhsi/s e)sti\ ta)lhqh= le/gein.

'Axes and torches had been brought against ye.' The entrance would have been forced by these Mohocks. Cf. Horace, Odes iii. 26. 7; Arist. Eccles. 977:



*g. kai\ th\n qu/ran g' h)/rattes. *n. a)poqa/noim' a)/ra.

*g. tou= dai\ deo/menos da=|d' e)/xwn e)lh/luqas;

mu/qwn  is used somewhat contemptuously. Contrast Aesch. P. V. 40:



a)nhkoustei=n de\ tw=n *patro\s lo/gwn

oi(=o/n te pw=s; ou) tou=to deimai/neis ple/on;

Cf. Horace, Od.iv. 3. 1:



'Quem tu Melpomene semel

Nascentem placido lumine videris';

but the resemblance of the rest is slight. The thought is rather like that of Propertius, iii. 16. 11:



'Nec tamen est quisquam sacros qui laedat amantes;

Scironis media sic licet ire via.

Quisquis amator erit Scythicis licet ambulet oris;

Nemo adeo, ut noceat, barbarus esse volet.'

The lover and the favoured of the Muses bear alike a sacred inviolable life.

to\ au)/rion  Attic of the best period says h( au)/rion, Eurip. Alc. 783 (adverbially ei)s au)/rion), and with a preposition omits the article altogether, me/xri e)xqe\s h)\ prw/hn, Demosth. xix. 260; ei)s nu=n, Plato, Tim. 20 b, etc.; Krüger, i. 66. 1. But with less definite designations of time the neuter article is common, to\ nu=n, to\ meta\ tau=ta, etc. For this cf. ii. 144 to\ e)xqe/s: Anacreont. ix:



to\ sh/meron me/lei moi

to\ d' au)/rion ti/s oi)=den;

tri/bontes a)/rotra  Verg. Georg. i. 46 'incipiat sulco attritus splendescere vomer'; Eurip. Ion 1, 2:



)/*atlas o( nw/tois xalke/oisin ou)rano\n

qew=n palaio\n oi)=kon e)ktri/bwn.

ti/s ga/r,  'then who of all who dwell beneath the grey dawn.' ga/r is used (in Homeric Greek) to introduce a question with a tone of impatience or surprise, Iliad i. 122:



)*atrei/dh ku/diste, filokteanw/tate pa/ntwn,

pw=s ga/r toi dw/sousi ge/ras mega/qumoi )*axaioi/;

Monro, Hom. Gram. § 348. 4. Here Theocritus after his introductory quatrain plunges abruptly into his complaint against greed.

kupa/rissos.  For the comparison cf. Omar Khayyám's 'the cypress--slender minister of wine'; Catull. lxi. 21 'floridis velut enitens Myrtus Asia ramulis'; Sappho, 104:



